5. JFrog + AWS CodePipeline / CodeBuild	CI/CD integration

Prerequisites

# Install required tools
# 1. AWS CLI
curl "https://awscli.amazonaws.com/awscli-exe-linux-x86_64.zip" -o "awscliv2.zip"
unzip awscliv2.zip && sudo ./aws/install

# 2. JFrog CLI
curl -fL https://install-cli.jfrog.io | sh
sudo mv jf /usr/local/bin/

# 3. Docker (for local Artifactory)
# Already assumed installed

Step 1 — Set up JFrog Artifactory (two options)
Option A: JFrog Cloud (recommended for laptop — no Docker overhead)

Go to jfrog.com/start-free → create a free cloud instance
Note your instance URL: https://<your-name>.jfrog.io
Create a generic or PyPI/npm/Maven repository (match your project type)
Option B: Local Docker

docker run -d --name artifactory \
  -p 8081:8081 -p 8082:8082 \
  -v $HOME/artifactory/data:/var/opt/jfrog/artifactory \
  releases-docker.jfrog.io/jfrog/artifactory-oss:latest
# Access at http://localhost:8082 (admin/password)

Step 2 — Configure AWS Account
# Configure AWS CLI (use free-tier account)
aws configure
# Enter: Access Key ID, Secret Access Key, region (e.g. us-east-1), output: json

# Store JFrog credentials in AWS Secrets Manager
aws secretsmanager create-secret \
  --name "jfrog/credentials" \
  --secret-string '{"JFROG_URL":"https://<your-name>.jfrog.io","JFROG_USER":"admin","JFROG_PASSWORD":"<your-token>"}'

Step 3 — Create a Sample Project
mkdir jfrog-codebuild-demo && cd jfrog-codebuild-demo
git init

# Simple Python project
cat > requirements.txt << 'EOF'
requests==2.31.0
EOF

cat > app.py << 'EOF'
import requests
print("Hello from CI/CD + JFrog!")
EOF

Step 4 — Create buildspec.yml (CodeBuild instructions)
# buildspec.yml
version: 0.2

env:
  secrets-manager:
    JFROG_URL: "jfrog/credentials:JFROG_URL"
    JFROG_USER: "jfrog/credentials:JFROG_USER"
    JFROG_PASSWORD: "jfrog/credentials:JFROG_PASSWORD"

phases:
  install:
    runtime-versions:
      python: 3.11
    commands:
      # Install JFrog CLI
      - curl -fL https://install-cli.jfrog.io | sh
      - mv jf /usr/local/bin/

  pre_build:
    commands:
      # Authenticate with JFrog
      - jf config add artifactory --url=$JFROG_URL --user=$JFROG_USER --password=$JFROG_PASSWORD --interactive=false
      - jf rt ping

  build:
    commands:
      - echo "Running build..."
      - pip install -r requirements.txt
      - python app.py
      # Package artifact
      - zip -r app-$CODEBUILD_BUILD_NUMBER.zip app.py requirements.txt

  post_build:
    commands:
      # Upload artifact to JFrog Artifactory
      - jf rt u "app-$CODEBUILD_BUILD_NUMBER.zip" "my-repo/builds/" --build-name=MyApp --build-number=$CODEBUILD_BUILD_NUMBER
      - jf rt bce MyApp $CODEBUILD_BUILD_NUMBER   # collect env info
      - jf rt bp MyApp $CODEBUILD_BUILD_NUMBER    # publish build info

artifacts:
  files:
    - "app-*.zip"

Step 5 — Push to AWS CodeCommit (or GitHub)
# Option A: CodeCommit
aws codecommit create-repository --repository-name jfrog-codebuild-demo
git remote add origin https://git-codecommit.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/v1/repos/jfrog-codebuild-demo
git add . && git commit -m "Initial commit"
git push origin main

# Option B: GitHub — just push normally and use it as source

Step 6 — Create CodeBuild Project (via AWS Console or CLI)
# Create IAM role for CodeBuild first
cat > codebuild-trust.json << 'EOF'
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [{
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Principal": {"Service": "codebuild.amazonaws.com"},
    "Action": "sts:AssumeRole"
  }]
}
EOF

aws iam create-role --role-name CodeBuildJFrogRole --assume-role-policy-document file://codebuild-trust.json

# Attach policies (SecretsManager, S3, CloudWatch)
aws iam attach-role-policy --role-name CodeBuildJFrogRole \
  --policy-arn arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/SecretsManagerReadWrite
aws iam attach-role-policy --role-name CodeBuildJFrogRole \
  --policy-arn arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/CloudWatchLogsFullAccess

# Create CodeBuild project
aws codebuild create-project \
  --name jfrog-demo-build \
  --source '{"type":"CODECOMMIT","location":"https://git-codecommit.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/v1/repos/jfrog-codebuild-demo"}' \
  --artifacts '{"type":"NO_ARTIFACTS"}' \
  --environment '{"type":"LINUX_CONTAINER","computeType":"BUILD_GENERAL1_SMALL","image":"aws/codebuild/standard:7.0"}' \
  --service-role CodeBuildJFrogRole

Step 7 — Create CodePipeline
# Via AWS Console: CodePipeline → Create Pipeline
# Stage 1: Source  → CodeCommit (or GitHub with OAuth)
# Stage 2: Build   → CodeBuild → select jfrog-demo-build project
# Stage 3: (optional) Deploy → S3 / ECS / Lambda
Or use the console at AWS → CodePipeline → Create pipeline — it's a 5-step wizard.

Step 8 — Trigger & Verify
# Trigger a build manually
aws codebuild start-build --project-name jfrog-demo-build

# Watch logs
aws codebuild batch-get-builds --ids <build-id> | jq '.builds[0].currentPhase'

# Verify artifact in JFrog
jf rt s "my-repo/builds/"

Architecture Summary
Git push
   │
   ▼
CodePipeline (Source stage)
   │
   ▼
CodeBuild (buildspec.yml)
   ├─ Pulls dependencies from JFrog (optional)
   ├─ Runs build + tests
   └─ Pushes artifact + build-info to JFrog Artifactory

Key Notes
Free tier limits: AWS CodeBuild gives 100 build minutes/month free; JFrog Cloud free tier has 2GB storage
Secrets: Always use AWS Secrets Manager or SSM — never hardcode JFrog credentials in buildspec.yml
JFrog Build Info: The jf rt bp command links the artifact back to the exact CodeBuild run, giving you full traceability
